   systems makes him your closest match вҖ” and he's going to love this topic.)

  ---
  Nissim has just described a blob-physics-based topic selection UI вҖ” agar.io-inspired вҖ” where blue blobs = proposed topics, green blobs
  = partner interests, red bumpy blobs = past BATbern events. Attraction/repulsion mechanics encode semantic similarity and recency.

  ---
  рҹ“Ҡ Mary: Oh Nissim, THIS is the kind of clue that makes the hairs on my arms stand up! You've actually already done something most
  clients never manage вҖ” you've translated a business problem (we don't know what topic resonates) into a mental model (blobs attracting
  and absorbing). That's rare. Let me capture what I'm hearing as the core requirements underneath the metaphor:

  The fundamental need is multi-signal topic resonance scoring made visceral, not numeric. You need to simultaneously feel: partner
  appetite (green), recency penalty (red drag), and external conference overlap risk (a fourth signal you mentioned, Swiss IT landscape вҖ”
   which I'd love to explore further). The blob mechanic makes all four signals readable at a glance, without a single percentage sign. I
   love it.

  My analytical instinct is screaming: we need to nail down what "similar" means across those 57 red blobs and the partner topics. Is "AI
   in Healthcare" similar to "Machine Learning in Clinical Settings"? That's the semantic layer that drives ALL the attraction physics.
  What's your current gut feel вҖ” do you have a taxonomy, or is this entirely free-form?

  ---
  рҹҺЁ Sally: leans in Oh wow. Okay. OKAY. Nissim, can I just say вҖ” you described this as "like the game Blob" and my brain immediately
  went to agar.io, and then further back to Osmos, the iOS game where you were an organism absorbing smaller things but fleeing larger
  ones. There's something emotionally satisfying about that mechanic that no bar chart will ever replicate. You feel the tension. You
  feel the fit.

  What I'm fascinated by from a UX perspective is the interaction moment вҖ” when does a blue blob come into existence? Does Nissim type a
  topic into a field and it spawns? Does it appear with a "pop"? Does it drift in from the edge of the screen? That spawning moment sets
  the entire emotional tone of the tool. And then watching the green partner blobs slowly drift toward it while the red past-event blobs
  push back... that's storytelling through physics.

  I also want to explore: what happens to the space when there are no blue blobs? You mentioned the backlog of topics + partner votes
  could auto-populate the field. What if the void itself slowly fills with "candidate ghosts" вҖ” semi-transparent topic ideas floating
  quietly вҖ” waiting to be "summoned" as blue blobs by the organizers? It creates a discovery mode.

  рҹ“Ҡ Mary to Sally: I love "candidate ghosts" вҖ” from a requirements standpoint, that maps perfectly to the backlog + partner topics as a
  pre-stage before a topic is "proposed." It solves the cold-start problem for when organizers have no ideas.

  ---
  рҹ“Ӣ John: taps table Right. Let's talk about what makes this actually work as a decision tool rather than a toy вҖ” because that line is
  razor-thin.

  The blob mechanic is brilliant, but only if the organizers trust the signals. Here's my gamification concern: feedback loops and
  agency. In agar.io you CONTROL your blob. Here, the blue blob's size is determined by emergent physics вҖ” you're an observer, not a
  player. That's a fundamentally different engagement model. It's closer to a simulation than a game, which is fine вҖ” but the interaction
   design has to acknowledge that.

  What I want to understand from you, Nissim: what's the decision moment? When do the organizers say "yes, this is our topic"? Is it when
   a blue blob reaches a certain size? Do you click to "lock in" a blob? Do you vote вҖ” and the voting itself makes the blob grow? Because
   that decision moment is where the gamification hooks need to land. The rest is beautiful visualization, but the commitment mechanic is
   what turns this from art into a tool.

  Also вҖ” nine partners, up to 20 green blobs вҖ” does each partner have a distinct color/pattern within the green family? So when
  "Swisscom" and "Post Finance" are both absorbed into a blue blob, you can actually see which partners are in there? That's valuable org
   intelligence, not just a count.

  ---
  рҹ“Ҡ Mary asks you, Nissim:

  I want to zoom in on the red blobs for a moment вҖ” the 57 past BATbern events. You said "the less time since that topic was selected,
  the more it is attracted to the blue blob." So a recent event on "Cloud Migration" would strongly repel a new "Cloud Migration" blue
  blob вҖ” making it smaller, draining its energy. But how far back does that penalty fade? Do events from 10 BATberns ago become neutral?
  And should there be a "sweet spot" вҖ” topics that were covered just long enough ago that the community is ready for a refresh?

  [Awaiting your response...]

