  в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ

  The AI doesn't need a general language model for "similarity" вҖ” it needs to map new input against these specific clusters. That's
  actually a much more tractable and trustworthy problem. A topic like "LLM Ops" should immediately pull toward the AI/ML cluster, and
  those 5 recent red blobs in that cluster would form a tight, buzzing cloud of resistance around any new AI blob. That's
  information-dense in a single glance.

  The 6-event neutralization rule maps beautifully onto roughly 3 years of BATbern history (assuming 2x/year). So the mental model is:
  "anything in the last 3 years is still fresh, anything before that is fair game." Clean. Memorable.

